Notes: General: Test food taken ad lib., other foods kept constant. Marker, carmine or carbo sanguinis. Plan of 2d report: Total period was 6 days. Some subjects not consistently in negative or positive N-balance during the series of experiments.

Subject S had diarrhea but differentiation of feces was good. Subject R in experimenet on flour No. 10 had severe stomach ache and diarrhea on 2d day.

Food: Wheat, Wheat Products (Triticum aestivum): Flours, intermediate extractions: 85-pct. extraction (patent, 1st and 2d clear, red dog, and shorts).
Species: 472 gm. bread (made of flour, yeast, salt, and water), oranges, butter, sugar, tea or coffee if desired.
Collected From: Merrill AL, Watt BK. ENERGY VALUE OF FOODS... basis and derivation (Agriculture Handbook No. 74) [Internet]. Washington DC: United States Department of Agriculture, Agricultural Research Service, Human Nutrition Research Branch; 1955 [cited Febuary 28 2024]. Original Source: LANGWORTHY, C. F. and HOLMES, A. D. 1921. THE EFFECT OF A VARIATION IN MILLING ON THE DIGESTIBILITY OF WHEAT FLOURS. Nati. Acad. Sci. Pro. 7: 119-123.
Notes: Subjects, young men, both active and sedentary. Series of 139 experiments made. Experimental periods of 15-26 days subdivided into separate sucessive 3-day periods in which bread from flours of 54-, 70-, 85-, and 100-percent extractions were fed in simple diets. Authors' customary expertmental procedure followed.

Food: Wheat, Wheat Products (Triticum aestivum): Flours, intermediate extractions: 85-pct. extraction
Species: 550 gm. bread made from 85-pct. extraction flour, fed in a mixed diet of meat, vegetables, paste, rice, lard, cheese, butter, sugar, cafe au lait, and wine.
Collected From: Merrill AL, Watt BK. ENERGY VALUE OF FOODS... basis and derivation (Agriculture Handbook No. 74) [Internet]. Original Source: PUGLTESE, A. 1915. LA VALEUR ALIMENTAIRE DES DIVERS TYPES DE PAIN. Rev. Gn. des Sci. Pures et Appl. 26: 612-617, illus.
Notes: Subjects, men, ages 22-37 Yr. Flours described in this item and items 133 and 143 tested in the following order in consecutive 5-day periods: 75-pct., 85-pct., and 80-pct. extraction. Collected From: Merrill AL, Watt BK. ENERGY VALUE OF FOODS... basis and derivation (Agriculture Handbook No. 74) [Internet]. Notes: Subjects, men. Experimental period, 1 wk. with 4 meals daily in which standard meal bread was fed. 3-wk. interval between this and preceding experiment of 1 wk. in which patent flour was test food. Marker, carmine. N-balance of subject I, +0.5 gm.; other 3 subjects in negative N-balance, averaging -1.3 gm. per day.

Food: Wheat, Wheat Products (Triticum aestivum): Flours, intermediate extractions: 80-pct. extraction, milled commercially from English wheat.
Species: Wheat flour made largely into bread; some made into pastries and cakes. Butter, bacon fat, bramble and marmalade jelly, weak tea or water if desired. 50 mg. ascorbic acid taken dally if remembered.
Collected From: Merrill AL, Watt BK. ENERGY VALUE OF FOODS... basis and derivation (Agriculture Handbook No. 74) [Internet]. Washington DC: United States Department of Agriculture, Agricultural Research Service, Human Nutrition Research Branch; 1955 [cited Febuary 28 2024]. Available from: https://www.ars.usda.gov/arsuserfiles/80400535/data/classics/usda%20handbook%2074.pdf
Original Source: MCCANCE, R. A., and WIDDOWSON, E. M. 1947. THE DIGESTIBILITY OF ENGLISH AND CANADIAN WHEATS WITH SPECIAL REFERENCE TO THE DIGESTIBILITY OF WHEAT PROTEIN BY MAN. Jour. Hyg. 45: 59-64.
Notes: Subjects, 2 men, 4 women. Experiment in 4 parts in which were tested flours of 90- and 80-pct. extraction from both English and Manitoba wheats. For each flour there was a 3-day preperiod, 7-day test period, and a postperiod. Carmine marker taken before 1st meal of test period and of postperiod. Feces collected in test period between appearances of carmine. Experiment planned to minimize effects of season, habits, etc.

Collected From: Merrill AL, Watt BK. ENERGY VALUE OF FOODS... basis and derivation (Agriculture Handbook No. 74) [Internet]. Washington DC: United States Department of Agriculture, Agricultural Research Service, Human Nutrition Research Branch; 1955 [cited Febuary 28 2024]. Original Source: CAHILL, W. M., SCHROEDER, L. J., and SMITH, A. H. 1944. DIGESTIBILITY AND BIOLOGICAL VALUE OF SOYBEAN PROTEIN IN WHOLE SOYBEANS, SOYBEAN FLOUR, AND SOYBEAN MILK. Jour. Nutr. 28: 209-218.
Notes: Subjects, young men. Experimental method of Murlin et al., 1941 (17), followed. Test food or egg supplied about 4/5 of the food N. Soybeans, soy flour, and soy milk tested in series of experiments planned so that an egg period always preceded and followed a soy products period. Experimental periods, 6 days. Marker, charcoal, taken with 1st meal of each period. N-balance of subjects positive in egg period, averaging +0.8 gm. per day; negative in soybean period, averaging -0.1 gm. per day. To calculate apparent digestibility of test food, N-intake and fecal N from the other foods were estimated from amounts in sample diet recorded by authors.

Readjustment period of 1 mo. for each subject between experiments.

Notes: Subjects, 11 men. 3-day period on a no-protein diet (the mixed basal diet with egg omitted) followed by 5-day experimental period in which yeast was added to diet. Urine collected in last 2 or 3 days of each period. In 5-day period following yeast period an amino acid mixture replaced yeast protein in the total diet. Average N-balance for no-protein diet period, -3.4 gm. and for yeast period, -1.0 gm. per day. 5 pct. of total N intake as approximate amount of N from other foods for calculating apparent digestibility of yeast.
